Sweetheart Deal: Chapter Sixteen - The Gladhand

Welcome to Nuevo Carcangel, circa 2174. A century has passed since a plague killed half of humanity. No one living now knows why some of the survivors are called chimeras, nor how the plague created them - if it did.
Christina Marlowe, a private investigator and a fox-type chimera, has other concerns. She's living in one of the biggest city-states. What technology used to exist is gone. She knows the trains and streetcars, her trusty revolver, and that she needs a big case.
Nathaniel Berrymount may be it. He's nervous at first and rightly so. The signs point to a sweetheart deal that's meant to collapse, leaving the victor with everything.
Marlowe will have to think and talk fast as events pile up. A Boss wants his blueprints back. What do the buns of The Warren want? And can she keep her client from falling for her?

In this chapter, what do you do after escaping yet again? Perhaps a drink is in order. To go with it, how about seeing who might want to buy into the deadly game at hand? Several aren't.
Marlowe's night won't be over until she learns why The Gladhand's owner is interested.
Oh, it's not over by a rather long shot.

Jasper Hollow sounds more like a housing development rather than a town.

Towns in the U.S are almost always named after some other place, the founder's name, Fort or Port, a native tribe or corruption thereof, a vague religious tone, something in another language or an obvious descriptor

The five biggest cities in the U.S prove that much
New York (York), Chicago (French Corruption of a native tribe), Los Angeles (Spanish), Dallas-Forth Worth (Dallas and a Fort), Houston (Named after Sam Houston the first president of Texas)
Some housing development names I've seen are "Merry Springs" "Oak Grove" "Green Pines" in towns like "No Trees", "Leeville" named after Robert E. Lee, Paris, or Germanton. (All real places, in Texas, Louisiana, Many States+France, North Carolina)
